                  <li class="program-course">
            <a href="/study/2014-2015/courses/poli-333" class="program-course-title">
              POLI 333 Western Political Theory 1 (3 credits)              <!---->            </a>
            <div class="program-course-description">
              <div class="program-course-description-inner">
                <div id="node-33865" class=" clearfix">
  
  
  
  <div class="meta">
    <p>Offered by: Political Science (<a href="/study/2014-2015/node/607">Faculty of Arts</a>)</p>
      </div>

  <div class="content">
    <h3>Overview</h3>

    <p>
      Political Science              : The major themes and writers in the political theory of classical antiquity. The political ideas of Thucydides, Plato, Aristotle, and the Hellenistic philosophers will be explored through the significant texts of this period.          </p>

    <p class="catalog-terms">
      Terms:              Fall 2014          </p>

    <p class="catalog-instructors">
      Instructors:                        William Roberts (Fall)                  </p>

    
          <ul class="catalog-notes">
              <li>Prerequisite: POLI 231 or POLI 232 or PHIL 240 or at least two political science courses at the 300 level; or permission of the instructor</li>
              <li>Note: The field is Political Theory.</li>
            </ul>
      </div>

  </div> <!-- /.node -->
